High levels of environmental protection - Passive observation that national measures should provide for high levels of environmental protection.
Commitment to enhance environmental protection - Active commitment to change national measures to provide better/higher levels of environmental protection over time.
Definition of environmental law - Formal definition of what constitutes environmental law, environmental measures, and related governance terms.
Not for protectionist purposes - Environmental measures should not be adopted for trade protectionist, discriminatory or unnecessary purposes.
Scientific knowledge when designing measures - Obligation to use scientific knowledge and technical data when designing, preparing, adopting or implementing environmental measures.
Scientific knowledge in environmental assessment - Obligation to consider scientific evidence in conducting environmental risk assessment.
Public participation in adoption of measures - Right of citizens, NGOs and stakeholders to participate in adoption of environmental measures through consultations, comments and participation.
Public participation in EIA - Right of public participation in environmental impact assessment for projects with significant environmental effects.
Environmental protection as precondition for trade or development - Environmental protection recognized as essential for growth, trade, liberalization or economic development.

Mutual supportiveness between environment and trade/development - Statement that protection of environment and trade/development ARE mutually supportive. Causal claims (is/are), not normative claims (should/could).

Recognition of development gap or different capabilities - Recognition of development gap between countries or of developing countries special needs and respective circumstances on environmental matters.
Cost-benefit analysis - Taking into account costs and benefits when designing environmental measures. Includes cost-effective environmental measures.
Business actors contribute to environmental protection - Recognition of role or contribution of private sector in environmental protection. Excludes NGO and civil society.
Inappropriate to encourage trade by relaxing environmental measures - Obligation not to encourage trade by weakening or reducing levels of protection in environmental laws.
Inappropriate to encourage investment by relaxing environmental measures - Obligation not to encourage investment by lowering domestic environmental standards.
Maintain existing level of environmental protection - Formal commitment to maintain at least the level of protection that exists.
Sovereignty over hydrobiological and fishery resources - Sovereign rights over fishery resources in territorial waters. Distinguished from protection of fishery resources (see 10.04.01).
Sovereignty over other specific resources - Includes sovereignty over minerals, water, forests, and other specific natural resources not otherwise classified.

Sovereignty in determining own environmental policies - Recognition of countries prerogative to establish their own levels of environmental protection, modify environmental laws and policies, and set priorities. Includes right to set protection level higher than minimum.

Sovereignty in the enforcement of environmental measures - Recognition of States discretion with respect to compliance matters and allocation of resources to enforcement. Includes Party ability to interpret its own measures.
Sovereignty or independence of national tribunals - Recognition of independence and sovereignty of national tribunals in applying environmental measures.
Other norms on regulatory sovereignty - Other norms on sovereignty over environmental regulation not elsewhere classified.
No extraterritorial enforcement activities - Explicit prohibition of enforcement activities in the territory of another Party.
No right of action under domestic law - No right of action under a Party domestic law against another Party on grounds of inconsistency with the agreement.
Environmental norm: 14 04 25 Other ref Agenda 2030 or Sustainable Development Goals

Common but differentiated responsibilities principle - Includes two necessary and joint elements: common responsibility of States to protect the environment, and the need to take into account different circumstances of a situation. Could be limited to a specific environmental issue such as climate change.

Prevention principle - Responsibility of States to ensure that activities within their jurisdiction do not cause damage to the environment. Refers to known risks rather than uncertainty (see 1.04 for precautionary principle).

Precautionary principle - Refers to preventing harm by taking action when there is lack of scientific certainty. Insufficient scientific evidence shall not be used as a reason to postpone or reject environmental measures.
Polluter pays principle - The polluter should bear the cost of pollution. Environmental externalities should be internalized. Includes mentions of extended producer responsibility.
Damage rectified at source - Aims to correct whatever damage is caused before it spreads to other areas. As opposed to prevention principle which aims to avoid causing damage at all.
Sovereignty over natural resources in general - Includes reference to sovereign right to exploit, conserve, administer and manage natural resources. Directly or indirectly expressed.
Sovereignty over genetic resources - Recognition of sovereign rights and authority over genetic resources as established by the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD).

Construction and environment - Environmental protection in construction activities including building energy performance.
Agriculture and environment - Environmental aspects in agricultural sector. Excludes specific issues like pesticides and GMOs.
Indigenous communities and environment - Role of indigenous communities and traditional knowledge in biodiversity conservation and sustainable use.
Human health and environment - Connection between environmental protection and human health.
Industrial activities and environment - Environmental protection in industrial activities, pollution and plant safety.
Transport and environment - Environmental aspects in all types of transportation (air, maritime, road, public).
Other non-environmental issues - Other interactions such as market economy transition, food security, regional development, culture.
Environmental norm: 5 01 01 Binding obligations
Energy and environment - Taking environmental concerns into account when designing energy policies. Distinguished from renewable energy promotion (see 10.15.01).
Mining and environment - Inclusion of environmental management and conservation measures in mining activities.
Tourism and environment - Environmental protection in tourism sector. Includes sustainable and ecotourism.
Gender and environment - Statement linking gender or womens issues to environmental protection as interacting issues.
Social issues and environment - Consideration of poverty, employment, labour, standard of living in relation to environmental protection.
Rural development and environment - Environmental aspects in sustainable rural development.
Urban development and environment - Environmental protection in urban development and urban pollution control.
Land use planning and environment - Linking land use planning to environmental concerns.
Publication of environmental laws - Obligation to publish and make available environmental laws, regulations and administrative decisions. Includes advance publication of proposed measures.
Identification in tariff terms - Obligation to identify environmental measures, restrictions or prohibitions according to tariff classification.
Monitor state of environment - Obligation to periodically prepare and publish reports on the state of the environment.
Environmental assessment requirement - Obligation to maintain appropriate procedures for assessing environmental impact of proposed projects with significant adverse effects.
Investment in environmental research - Commitment to invest in environmental research and science to improve State own environmental capacity.
National standards bodies - Obligation to establish or support national organisms for environmental standardization.
Coherence in general - General commitment to coherence between environmental policies and other economic/sectoral policies.
Coherence with trade/investment - Normative commitment to design trade and investment policies that are supportive with environmental protection.
